<h1>A Guide to Using Myanmar Unicode</h1>
<h2>OpenOffice</h2>
<div>
<p>
You can download a version of the Open Source Office Suite OpenOffice 3 with Myanmar support from the links at <a href="http://my.openoffice.org/">my.openoffice.org</a>. This now includes support for Myanmar word based line breaking. If you install the <a href="../../Downloads/#OOoGr">Myanmar dictionary</a> then it also has some spell checking support. As of OpenOffice 3.1 the main version of OpenOffice includes a Myanmar locale with Myanmar sorting support.</p>
<p>If you would like to help with translating (localizing) OpenOffice into Myanmar, then please have a look at the <a href="http://pootle.sunvirtuallab.com/my/">Pootle site</a>.</p>
<p>On Windows you can type using Keyman. On Linux, you must configure SCIM to use XIM “On the spot” mode (in the Front End / X Window Setup options) for KMFL to work correctly with OpenOffice. 
</p>
</div>
